{
  "final_answer": "## Connectivity Segment — FY2025 YoY Growth Analysis\n\n### Summary Financial Table (Recast Consolidated Basis)\n\n| Metric | FY2024 | FY2025 | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Revenue** | $7,599M | $11,387M | **+49.8%** |\n| **Operating Income** | $2,006M | $4,423M | **+120.5%** |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | $3,849M | $7,168M | **+86.2%** |\n\n### Margin Expansion\n\n| Margin Metric | FY2024 | FY2025 | Change |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Operating Margin | 26.4% | 38.8% | **+1,240 bps** |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA Margin | 50.7% | 62.9% | **+1,230 bps** |\n\n### Segment Adjusted EBITDA Reconciliation Bridge\n\n| Component | FY2024 | FY2025 | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Operating Income | $2,006M | $4,423M | +120.5% |\n| + Depreciation & Amortization | $1,508M | $2,376M | +57.6% |\n| + Share-Based Compensation | $296M | $369M | +24.7% |\n| + Impairment | $39M | $0M | — |\n| **= Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$3,849M** | **$7,168M** | **+86.2%** |\n\n---\n\n### Operating Leverage Analysis\n\nThe differential growth rates reveal **powerful and multi-layered operating leverage** within the Connectivity segment:\n\n**1. Operating Income grew 2.4× faster than revenue (120.5% vs. 49.8%).**\nThis is the clearest signal of operating leverage. As Starlink's subscriber base scaled to ~10.3 million (approximately +105% YoY), the segment's largely fixed-cost satellite network infrastructure allowed incremental revenue to flow through to operating profit at a dramatically higher rate. The ~1,240 bps operating margin expansion (from 26.4% to 38.8%) confirms that the marginal cost of serving additional subscribers is well below the segment's average cost, consistent with the filing's description of \"minimal marginal cost\" for the LEO satellite architecture.\n\n**2. Segment Adjusted EBITDA grew 1.7× faster than revenue (86.2% vs. 49.8%), but materially slower than Operating Income.**\nThe gap between Operating Income growth (+120.5%) and Adj. EBITDA growth (+86.2%) is explained by **D&A growing at +57.6%**, outpacing revenue growth. This reflects the capital-intensive satellite deployment cycle — as SpaceX continues to launch new satellites (over 9,600 in orbit as of Q1 2026), the associated capitalized costs are depreciated, creating a growing D&A charge that partially offsets operating leverage at the EBITDA level. D&A expanded from $1,508M to $2,376M (+$868M), absorbing roughly 23% of the incremental revenue.\n\n**3. SBC grew only +24.7%, well below revenue growth.**\nShare-based compensation grew from $296M to $369M — a modest increase that further contributed to margin expansion, indicating that headcount-related equity costs are not scaling proportionally with revenue.\n\n**4. ARPU headwinds make the leverage story even more impressive.**\nThe filing discloses that FY2025 average ARPU declined ~11.2% YoY (to $81/month) as Starlink expanded into emerging markets with localized, lower-priced plans. Despite this per-unit pricing pressure, the segment still achieved massive margin expansion — indicating that volume-driven scale effects and cost efficiencies far outweighed ARPU dilution.\n\n### Implications\n\nThe differential growth rates imply that Connectivity has passed the **inflection point** typical of capital-intensive network businesses:\n\n- **Near-term:** The fixed-cost nature of the satellite constellation means each incremental subscriber contributes high-margin revenue. Operating leverage should persist as the subscriber base grows, though the rate of margin expansion may moderate as the segment scales.\n- **D&A as a headwind to EBITDA leverage:** The faster growth of D&A vs. revenue means that Operating Income will continue to exhibit greater leverage than Adj. EBITDA. This gap will narrow only when the satellite deployment cadence stabilizes or when next-generation Starship/V3 satellites (with 20× the downlink capacity per launch) drive down cost-per-bit.\n- **Structural advantage:** The combination of a scalable space-based architecture, vertical integration, and declining launch costs (via Falcon reusability and future Starship) positions Connectivity for sustained margin expansion — a rare profile for a business still growing revenue at ~50%.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
